[3] Safe burials
Tue 7 Aug 2018. DRC-Ebola: ICRC and Red Cross team in Beni for "safe" burials of victims [actualite.CD., machine trans., edited]
https://actualite.cd/2018/08/07/rdc-ebola-cicr-et-une-equipe-de-la-croix-rouge-a-beni-pour-les-inhumations-sans-risque-des-victimes/


A team from the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC), the Red Cross of the DRC, and the International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies arrived in Beni (North Kivu) on Tue 7 Aug 2018 to contribute to the response to the reported Ebola outbreak in the locality of Mangina. Comprised of 19 members, the multidisciplinary team will notably facilitate the safe burials of the victims of the disease. Some members of the team contributed to the eradication of the Ebola epidemic a few weeks ago in Equateur province (West).

"The Ebola virus is the most contagious just after the death of the sick. It is therefore essential, in order to stop its spread, to follow security procedures for the management of human remains in case of suspicion of Ebola. But for this approach to work, it needs to be adapted to local cultural beliefs and norms, which means engaging with communities and gaining their trust. This crucial process will be one of the priorities of the Red Cross teams," said Dr Fatoumata Nafo-Traore, regional director of the International Federation for Africa, in a statement released on Tuesday [7 Aug 2018].

The epidemiological situation of the disease as of Sun 5 Aug 2018 is 43 cases of haemorrhagic fever reported in the region, of which 16 are confirmed and 27 probable, and 4 new deaths of confirmed cases in Mabalako.

The ICRC regrets that this disease adds to the problem of insecurity in this part of the country. "The people of northern North Kivu province have already experienced the effects of armed conflict for years. We are very concerned about the devastating impact that an Ebola outbreak could have on these fragile communities," said Nicolas Lambert, deputy head of the ICRC delegation in the DRC.

According to the authorities, this 10th epidemic has already killed at least 33 people since last May [2018]. Health authorities have announced the start of Ebola vaccination in Beni on Wednesday [8 Aug 2018]. The operation will initially concern the nursing staff.

[byline: Patrick Maki]

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail rapporteur Mary Marshall

["Safe Burials" is one of the key pillars of Ebola outbreak control and requires true awareness and sensitivity of local cultural beliefs and practices in order to gain the community's trust. - Mod.LXL]

