[4] Security issues
- Wed 8 Aug 2018. Congo turmoil means Ebola vaccinators will need armed escorts, experts warn.
[The Guardian, excerpted, edited]
https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2018/aug/08/congo-turmoil-ebola-vaccinators-will-need-armed-escorts-world-health-organization-warn


Armed escorts will be required to protect vaccination teams as they battle to contain Ebola in the DRC, WHO has warned. The Ebola outbreak area in North Kivu province, classified as a level-4 security threat by WHO -- one of the highest set by the UN -- comes amid local unrest, including violence between rival militia groups. The turmoil poses major challenges for those tasked with locating and vaccinating people who may have come into contact with Ebola victims.

"Even though we have access to the towns of Mangini and Beni, we don't know to what extent we will be able to rely on armed escorts for broader contact tracing outside those small towns. That's going to be a critical determining factor in our ability to respond," said spokesman Tarik Jasarevic.

So far there have been 43 cases, of which 16 are confirmed; 34 people have died. The cost of the response, said WHO, "is likely to be significant."

The UN peacekeeping force in DRC, which has more than 20 000 personnel, is already playing a key role, while the WHO, UNICEF, the World Food Programme, the International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies, and Médecins Sans Frontières (MSF, also known as Doctors Without Borders) also have people in Kinshasa or the area of the outbreak.

[byline: Sarah Boseley]

- Wed 8 Aug 2018, corrected Thu 9 Aug 2018. War zone complicates roll-out of Ebola vaccine in latest outbreak
[Nature magazine, excerpted and edited]
https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-018-05921-4


Aid workers in the DRC began giving an experimental Ebola vaccine to health workers on [Wed 8 Aug 2018, one week after WHO declared an outbreak of the virus. 1st responders and public-health staff are scrambling to contain the outbreak while planning how to roll out the vaccine to communities in the middle of a conflict zone.

The virus is spreading in North Kivu and Ituri, in the east of the DRC. As of Tue 7 Aug 2018, 44 people had shown symptoms of Ebola, including 36 who had died. But violence perpetuated by more than 100 armed groups fighting over resources and power in those lush, green provinces has escalated this year in advance of the country's presidential election scheduled for December [2018]. This is the nation's 10th Ebola outbreak since 1976, but it is the 1st in this tumultuous eastern region.

"The situation is volatile," says Ibrahima Soce-Fall, director of the WHO's operations in Africa, based in Brazzaville in the neighbouring Republic of Congo. Even so, researchers are also gearing up to give people with Ebola experimental antibody and antiviral drugs in addition to the vaccine.

Soce-Fall says that at least 2000 doses of the experimental vaccine, called rVSV-ZEBOV, remain in the country from the most recent Ebola outbreak, which ended in July [2018], and more doses are on the way. The DRC will need a larger vaccine supply now because the strategy deployed during the previous outbreak will not work for the current one. That last outbreak, which hit western DRC, lasted 3 months.

During the previous outbreak, officials vaccinated health workers, people who had direct contact with someone with Ebola, and the contacts of those contacts. But the instability in North Kivu and Ituri has made tracking such connections difficult. In towns where people have been infected but officials can't track down their contacts, workers might vaccinate the entire community instead, says Soce-Fall.

An inability to track these connections worries epidemiologists, because the virus spreads through people on the move. Humanitarian groups estimate that nearly 750 000 people in North Kivu and Ituri have fled this year from militia fighters who maim and rape people and burn villages to the ground. And about one million refugees who have been displaced from their homes by fighting over at least the past decade continue to travel frequently between cities in the region. Some refugees migrate through the porous borders of neighbouring countries such as Uganda, Rwanda, and Burundi.

Aid agencies must now figure out how to get into these conflict zones to fight Ebola without endangering their staff. Workers might travel with armed security escorts provided by the DRC government for their protection, said Peter Salama, WHO's head of emergency preparedness and response, at a press briefing on [Fri 3 Aug 2018].

But a key organization fighting Ebola in the area, MSF, hesitates to use that approach. The group feels that travelling with armed escorts hinders their ability to help people of various political affiliations, says Salha Issoufou, the head of MSF's operation in DRC. So MSF will forgo the escorts.

[byline: Amy Maxmen]

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail rapporteur Mary Marshall

[Not only Ebola vaccinators, but all epidemiological personnel including contact tracers and safe burial teams, may need armed escorts. This will add layers of logistical issues, because obviously these functions do not occur simultaneously in a given locale, necessitating more armed escort teams and/or longer-term security deployments. How will security forces react if attacked by armed insurgents? Are supplies and equipment (for example, for vaccination) as well as personnel at risk of kidnapping? What if Ebola spreads into one of the many shadowy Congolese insurgent groups well-accustomed to hiding from government authorities? Many unprecedented scenarios, some horrific to contemplate, could arise from the present juxtaposition of a lethal outbreak and armed insurgencies. - Mod.LXL]

